definition.value: A chlorophyllide obtained by hydrolysis of the terpenoid ester moiety of 3-(1-hydroxyethyl)bacteriochlorophyll a.
A chlorophyllide obtained by hydrolysis of the terpenoid ester moiety of 3-(1-hydroxyethyl)chlorophyll a.
A chlorophyllide obtained by hydrolysis of the terpenoid ester moiety of bacteriochlorophyll a.
A chlorophyllide obtained by hydrolysis of the terpenoid ester moiety of 3-vinylbacteriochlorophyll d.
A chlorophyllide obtained by hydrolysis of the terpenoid ester moiety of any bacteriochlorophyll d.
A chlorophyllide obtained by hydrolysis of the terpenoid ester moiety of any bacteriochlorophyll c.
A resolvin that is (6Z,8E,10E,14Z,16E)-icosa-6,8,10,14,16-pentaenoic acid which is substituted at positions 5, 12 and 18 by hydroxy groups (the 5S,12R,18R stereoisomer).
A member of the class of resolvins that is (6E,8Z,11Z,14Z,16E)-icosapentaenoic acid carrying two hydroxy substituents at positions 5 and 18 (the 5S,18R stereoisomer).
An 18-HEPE that consists of (5Z,8Z,11Z,14Z,16E)-icosapentaenoic in which the 18-hydroxy group has R-configuration.
A resolvin that is docosa-4Z,9E,11E,13Z,15E,19Z-hexaenoic acid which is substituted by hydroxy groups at the 7, 8, and 17 positions (the 7S,8R,17S-stereoisomer).
A member of the class of resolvins that is (4Z,8E,10Z,12E,14E,19Z)-docosahexaenoic acid carrying three hydroxy substituents at positions 7, 16 and 17 (the 7S,16R,17S-stereoisomer).

A group of small, cationic polypeptides (consisting of 12-97 amino acids) that are found in humans and other species, including farm animals (E.g. cattle, horses, pigs, sheep etc). They show a broad spectrum of antimicrobial activity against bacteria, enveloped viruses and fungi.
A polybromodiphenyl ether that is diphenyl ether in which the hydrogens at the 2, 4, 5, 2', and 4' positions have been replaced by bromines.
